Manufacturer Part No: MTM-000-A4
- Integrated Visible Red Marking Laser
- Menu-Driven Functions
- Facial Recognition at 25 Meters
- Digital Image Capture & Download
- Run Time of 3 Hours
- Waterproof to 66'
- Three Hours of Continuous Operation Using Two 3V Lithium Batteries (123)

Insight Tech-Gear's hand-held thermal imager provides stationary man-sized target detection performance over 400 meters. It's compact, lightweight form and exceptional image quality make the MTM a versatile tool for a wide range of missions, including reconnaissance, surveillance, and search & rescue.

The MTM features a high resolution 320 x 240 focal plane array with a 2x digital zoom. The Mini Thermal Monocular is lightweight, pocket-sized and ergonomically designed for handheld operation. It has an adjustable focus and standby operating mode. With a quick start up time, the monocular is fully operational and imaging in less than 5 seconds from power up. The MTM runs up to 4 hours of continuous operation using two 3-Volt Lithium batteries. The thermal monocular features both white/hot and black/hot polarity and is waterproof up to 66 feet. With digital image capture and download at up to 160 images, the MTM has facial recognition at 25 meters, stationary man-sized target detection at 400 meters and moving man-sized target detection at 500 meters.

8,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2928008,"For Sale:   AK-74 (5.45x39) with magazines, ammo, and carry bag","Gilbert, Phoenix, Arizona",$ 825,"Listed On: Thursday, April 10, 2014",Rifles,no type,5.45x39mm                                                                                ,Semi-automatic                                                                                ,Rifle,"For sale is an M74 Sporter AK-74, package includes the following:
- The rifle
- ~400 rounds of ammo:

column2: 120 rds. of new manufacture Red Army Standard ammo
Approximately 280 rds. of surplus ammo (I'm estimating there's about 20 rds. in the two opened bags. All the others are unopened with 30 rds.)

column1: - 6 magazines total:
- Carry bag
Didn't use this rifle much but it performed flawlessly when I did. Cleaned it after every outing and it wasn't bump-fired or anything that would cause undue stress.

The smaller 5.45x39 ammo compared to it's big brother gives an almost non-existent recoil impulse, so it's comfortable to shoot even for novices/younger people. It's also demonstrated excellent accuracy even with surplus ammo, it's probably one of the best AR alternatives on the market.
18+ with valid AZ DL, local sale only. Just need a photo of your Arizona driver's license, no bill of sale needed. Not interested in trades since I'm putting money from this toward school.
Located on the East side in Gilbert, but can definitely travel within reason to meet.
Thanks for looking!
Keywords - AK-74, AK 74, 5.45, 5.45x39, rifle, century arms, CAI"

500,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2928500,For Sale:  7.62x54 Ammo - The Unusual/Hard to Find Stuff,"Brandon, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida",$ 1,"Listed On: Wednesday, April 16, 2014",Ammo,no type,no type,no type,no type,"Here's an assortment of 7.62 x 54 ammo that I dug out of my ammo locker recently that's become hard to find these days:

(5) 20 round boxes of Hungarian Silver/Yellow Tip. This ammo was made in the late 80's which is practically brand new in the world of 7.62x54 ammo. It features a heavy FMJ 182 grain bullet with a steel core. It's loaded in lacquered steel cases giving it a pleasant gray appearance. The bullet and primer are both sealed with a red lacquer. I've shot a ton of this long ago when it was available and it's some of the very best ammo I've ever used. It's quite accurate, packs a heavy punch and it penetrates like crazy- far more than the light ball steel core ammo available today. The only flaw with this ammo is that recoil is noticeably heavier. Asking $75 for the 100 rounds.

(5) 20 round boxes Russian made Match Ammo. This ammo was specifically loaded for accuracy. Tolerances are tighter and it uses a match grade propellant. It's brass case with a heavy FMJ 182 grain boat-tail bullet. The box is marked 1971, but it is bright, shiny and sure fire. It's without a doubt the most accurate ammo of this caliber that I've ever shot and I was able to routinely achieve sub-MOA 5 shot groups with a nice Finnish M27 rifle I used to own. It also performed very nicely in my Mosins and a SVT40. Asking $90 for the 100 rounds.

(5) 20 round boxes East German M39 7.62x54 ammo. M39 ammo was originally designed as practice/training ammo primarily for machine guns. It's loaded with special black 124 grain FMJ steel core bullet. Velocity is not reduced, and the thought process was that the lighter projectile would travel less far than standard weight bullets. It's definitely not your typical training ammo as it penetrates 1/4"" steel plate with ease at 100 yards. One big benefit is that felt recoil is greatly reduced because of the light weight 124 grain bullet making it suitable for younger shooters and the ladies. This ammo is nearly impossible to find anymore and I've had it stashed away for many years. Asking $100 for the 100 rounds.
Pickup in the Brandon area. You must be at least 21 to purchase."
